result.execSummary:
The defendant Taiwan R Neal was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Criminal Damage to Property [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Original PLEA/SENTENCING HEARING Transcript (32 pages) commencing AUGUST 12, 2014 received and filed.

Defendant Taiwan R Neal in court with attorney Anne M. Jaspers with Gabriela Leija (under the student practice rule).  
Defendant Taiwan R Neal in custody.  Michael Schindhelm appeared for the State of Wisconsin.      
 Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered COUNT #1, dismissed and read-in for the purposes of sentencing.  This now makes this case a misdemeanor.  

 AS TO COUNTS #2 and #3: Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty as charged in the Information/Complaint. Judgment of conviction entered.   The Court finds that the State has complied with victim notification.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT #2: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 2 YEARS, (CONSECUTIVE to count #3 and any other  sentences), with credit for 0 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 1 YEAR. 

AS TO COUNT #3: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 2 YEARS, (CONSECUTIVE to count #2 and any other sentences), with credit for 0 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 1 YEAR. 
The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is not eligible for the "Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program".  

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION: 
* Successfully complete "Batterers intervention"
   counseling and continue programming.
* Attend and complete parenting classes.
* Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
   and successfully complete recommended treatment.
* Random urine screens and breathalyzer test.
* Maintain absolute sobriety.  No drugs.  No alcohol.
* Successfully complete any other counseling and/or
   treatment deemed appropriate.
* No contact with victim, Tenitra H.  
* 3rd party contact for the purpose of time with children 
   as approved by agent.  No unsupervised contact with children. 
* Obtain and maintain employment.
* No firearms; weapons.
* Pay restitution in the amount of $155.28 to the Milwaukee Police Dept. 
* Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.
Court ordered defendant to pay all costs, fees, and surcharges, including DV surcharge (only applies to count #2), to be paid from 25% of prison funds, and if not paid during period of extended supervision, case converts to a civil judgment. Defendant advised of right to seek postconviction relief, and appeal. Due to this DV conviction he may never possess firearms or ammunition.
